@node "1_0" "News for this release"
@{fg fill}@{u}1. News for this release@{uu}@{fg text}
The main changes are:

* @{b}Really@{ub} fixed WHLoad games not working when they use "kick34005.A500". AmigaOS4.1 Update 5 must have been installed first.

Please see the @{"9. History" link "9_0"} chapter for a full summary of recent changes.


@{b}Note that I no-longer have time to heavily test RunInUAE myself, so PLEASE report any bugs or problems that you notice!@{ub}

@{"1.1. Existing users READ ME!" link "1_1"}
@endnode

@node "1_1" "Existing users READ ME!"
@{fg fill}@{u}1.1. Existing users READ ME!@{uu}@{fg text}
If you are used to RunInUAE r6 or earlier, then note that RunInUAE r7's menus & window now work quite differently (and in general should be much easier). Please make sure that you re-read the @{"4. Using RunInUAE" link "4_0"} chapter, and also the @{"5.2. The Per-game settings menu" link "5_2"} section.


@endnode

@node "2_0" "Introduction"
@{fg fill}@{u}2. Introduction@{uu}@{fg text}
RunInUAE is intended to make it incredibly easy to run old Amiga games on AmigaOS4, and it comes with an easy installer, so that you can:

* Run almost any HD installed 68k game (or program) inside E-UAE, by simply double-clicking on it!  Including WHDLoad & JOTD JST installed games.

* Run ADF & DMS games by double-clicking them.  (Needs a little bit of manual set-up if you don't have at least AmigaOS4.1 Update 4.) Otherwise just drag & drop them onto RunInUAE's icon in AmiDock or it's AppIcon.

* Run CD32 & CDTV games from real or virtual CDs.  (Compatibility is not great.)

* The installer can set-up E-UAE with full-speed Sam-optimised settings.  But it can also use your existing E-UAE settings if you want.

* The installer will get the necessary Kickstart ROMs from AmigaOS4.1 Update 4 (if you are using it), or otherwise it can copy them off an Amiga Forever CD.

* You do @{b}not@{ub} need to set-up any assignments, nor create or edit any cryptic scripts or config files, for it to work!  (Unlike alternative solutions.)

* You do not need RunInUAE running in the background, @{b}unless@{ub} you want to play HD installed 68k games that do @{b}not@{ub} use WHDLoad.


@endnode

@node "3_0" "Installation"
@{fg fill}@{u}3. Installation@{uu}@{fg text}
1.  Double-click on RunInUAE's "Install" icon, and answer any questions.   Please note that installation is a lot easier if you are using AmigaOS4.1 Update 4 (or later), or you have an Amiga Forever CD, because then it can get the required Kickstart ROMs & Workbench files from them.

If you don't have E-UAE amigfx v0.8.29 already installed, then I recommend you let the installer install it (especially Sam440 users).  You can have more than one version of E-UAE installed.  @{fg shadow}(This version of E-UAE is the fastest & most compatible version currently available.)@{fg text}

If you are not using AmigaOS4.1 Update 4 @{fg shadow}(or later)@{fg text}, and do not have an Amiga Forever CD, then a @{b}fake@{ub} Workbench 3.1 will be created, but please be warned that this is not as compatible as the real thing.  @{i}Also note that "Basic Workbench mode" does not work with the fake Workbench.@{ui}

If there were any installation issues, they should be displayed in a "RunInUAE installer errors" window.  Close this window when you don't need it.  If installation failed, then you can try running the installer again.  Please email me if you cannot get it to install (you can get my address from the @{"8. Last words & contact details" link "8_0"} chapter).


2.  As long as you didn't create a @{b}fake@{ub} Workbench 3.1, then you can check RunInUAE installed OK:  First click on the RunInUAE icon in AmiDock, to get it's window to appear, then choose the "Boot Workbench" item from it's "Control E-UAE" menu.  After some seconds you should see Workbench 3.1 appear full screen.  Please note that Workbench uses a 640x256 screen, but by usually E-UAE shows it in a scrollable 320x256 screen, so that games look good but run fast.

You can now quit E-UAE (by pressing Ctrl-Alt-Q).

@{b}HOWEVER, if your monitor was not able to display the 320x256 screen, or it did not appear full screen, then you need to make RunInUAE use 640x480 instead.  You can do this using the "Shared settings > Set default screen size to > 640x480" menu option for RunInUAE's window.@{ub} Performance will not be quite as good, so you may wish to read the @{"6.1. How to get RunInUAE working with your monitor" link "6_1"} section.

NOTE:  It will automatically use 640x480 for RadeonHD cards (such as in the AmigaOne X1000).


@{"3.1. Optional installation" link "3_1"}
@endnode

@node "3_1" "Optional installation"
@{fg fill}@{u}3.1. Optional installation@{uu}@{fg text}
If you don't have AmigaOS4.1 Update 4 (or later), and you want to be able to double-click on an ADF file to run it, then you need to configure this manually:

Start Sys:Prefs/DefIcons, then scroll down to & select "diskarchive" @{fg shadow}(or "archive" if you can't find it)@{fg text} in the Filetypes list.  Click on the Add button at the bottom of the list, and in the Name field delete "«new»", type "adf" (without quotes), and then press the Enter key.

Under the Actions box click on the Add...  button, and choose PATTERN.  In the Pattern field that appears underneath, you should type "#?.adf" (without quotes), and then press the Enter key.

Finally click on the Save button.


@endnode

@node "4_0" "Using RunInUAE"
@{fg fill}@{u}4. Using RunInUAE@{uu}@{fg text}
When RunInUAE is started, you should find that RunInUAE opens a small window in the middle of the Workbench screen.

This window tells you which game the "Per-game settings" menu is for.  Normally it shows the last game that was run using E-UAE, but dropping a game on the window makes it show that instead.  You can then change the game's settings using the "Per-game settings" menu.

This window has some menus which you may find useful:

* The "RunInUAE" menu contains the "Hide" item, which will hide the window.  You can get it back by either (1) double-clicking it's AppIcon @{fg shadow}(on the Workbench)@{fg text}, (2) using the Exchange commodity to Show it, or (3) using it's hot-key (if you have defined one in it's Tooltypes).  The "Start hidden" item allows you to set the window to be hidden when RunInUAE starts.  The "About" item gives version, copyright & contact information.  The "Help" item opens this "RunInUAE.guide" file, if it exists in RunInUAE's folder.

* The "Shared settings" menu allows you to change settings that are always used (by E-UAE & RunInUAE).  See @{"5.1. The Shared settings menu" link "5_1"} section for more info.

* The "Per-game settings" menu allows you to change settings that are specific to the game you last ran OR which you dropped on RunInUAE's window.  See @{"5.2. The Per-game settings menu" link "5_2"} section for more info.

* The "Control E-UAE" menu allows you to command E-UAE to do something (which obviously means E-UAE must already be running).  These changes are never saved, and only affect E-UAE until it quits.  See @{"5.3. The Control E-UAE menu" link "5_3"} section for more info.


RunInUAE is a commodity, so you can add it to your WBStartup.  In that case you will probably want to stop it's window from appearing, by ticking the "RunInUAE > Start hidden" menu item.  RunInUAE's icon also has some toolypes that you can change:

If you dislike RunInUAE's Workbench AppIcon, then you can disable that by setting it's APPICON tooltype to NO.

The initial position of RunInUAE's window can be specified using the tooltypes WIN_XPOS and WIN_YPOS.


@{"4.1. Running WHDLoad/JST games" link "4_1"}
@{"4.2. Running other HD installed games" link "4_2"}
@{"4.3. Running ADF (& DMS) games" link "4_3"}
@{"4.4. Running CD32 & CDTV games" link "4_4"}
@{"4.5. Using the eGame launcher" link "4_5"}
@endnode

@node "4_1" "Running WHDLoad/JST games"
@{fg fill}@{u}4.1. Running WHDLoad/JST games@{uu}@{fg text}
As described in the Introduction, using Workbench you can double-click on a game installed using WHDLoad (or JOTD JST).  It should run that game in E-UAE.

When you have finished with that game, you can quit E-UAE by pressing Ctrl-Alt-Q, or reset it by pressing Ctrl-Alt-R.

@{b}Warning!@{ub} When pressing Ctrl-Alt-hotkey in E-UAE, please make sure to press (and hold) the Ctrl key first, followed by the Alt key, followed by the hotkey. Otherwise it will not work.

@{b}Warning!@{ub} Please do NOT install WHDLoad on AmigaOS4, as this will break RunInUAE's WHDLoad redirection.  If you want to update WHDLoad, then you must do so from @{b}inside@{ub} E-UAE (by using "Boot Workbench").


@endnode

@node "4_2" "Running other HD installed games"
@{fg fill}@{u}4.2. Running other HD installed games@{uu}@{fg text}
As described in the Introduction, using Workbench you can double-click on any HD installed 68k game or program.  It should then run in E-UAE!  @{b}Please note that RunInUAE must already be running@{ub}, because it has to patch Workbench.  @{fg shadow}(Since it is a commodity, you can add it to your WBStartup.  You will probably want to stop it's window from appearing, by ticking the "RunInUAE > Start hidden" menu item.)@{fg text}

You can also drag & drop any HD installed game icon (including WHDLoad/JST ones) onto RunInUAE's icon in AmiDock, or on to RunInUAE's AppIcon.

When you have finished with that game, you can quit E-UAE by pressing Ctrl-Alt-Q, or reset it by pressing Ctrl-Alt-R.

@{b}Warning!@{ub} When pressing Ctrl-Alt-hotkey in E-UAE, please make sure to press (and hold) the Ctrl key first, followed by the Alt key, followed by the hotkey. Otherwise it will not work.


@{b}Also note@{ub} that if you are using a @{b}fake@{ub} Workbench 3.1 installation (because you are not using AmigaOS4.1 Update 4, and do not have an Amiga Forever CD), then you are likely to find that some games will not run (you may see an error requester).  This is because of missing Workbench files, which can only be obtained from a real Workbench 3.1 disk.


@endnode

@node "4_3" "Running ADF (& DMS) games"
@{fg fill}@{u}4.3. Running ADF (& DMS) games@{uu}@{fg text}
For Amiga games where you have the disk in ADF format (zipped or otherwise), you can drag & drop it onto RunInUAE's icon in AmiDock, or onto RunInUAE's AppIcon. It should then run that game in E-UAE.

You can also double-click on ADF disks (not zipped ones), and it should run that using E-UAE too.  Note that this needs a bit of manual installation, if you don't have at least AmigaOS4.1 Update 4 (see the @{"3.1. Optional installation" link "3_1"} section).

When you have finished with that game, you can quit E-UAE by pressing Ctrl-Alt-Q.

@{b}Warning!@{ub} When pressing Ctrl-Alt-hotkey in E-UAE, please make sure to press (and hold) the Ctrl key first, followed by the Alt key, followed by the hotkey. Otherwise it will not work.


@{b}Beware that AGA games will not run@{ub} unless their file name, or one of it's folder names, has the word AGA in it.  

For multi-disk ADF games, RunInUAE will automatically try to load up to 3 more disks, @{b}although not all games support this@{ub}.  And for RunInUAE to spot multiple disks:
* @{i}They must all have the same filename,@{ui} except for their disk number.
* The first disk must be number 1.
* The disk number should be after any other number.  (You can ensure this by putting it at the end of filename, just before the .ADF or .DMS or .ZIP)

For example:
  PinballFantasies-1.adf
  PinballFantasies-2.adf
  PinballFantasies-3.adf

However, it has been reported that Turrican 3 freezes when it tries to load from the second disk drive (I guess it is buggy).  So in that case you must rename the second Turrican 3 disk, so that RunInUAE does *not* automatically load it!


@endnode

@node "4_4" "Running CD32 & CDTV games"
@{fg fill}@{u}4.4. Running CD32 & CDTV games@{uu}@{fg text}
To run a CD32 or CDTV game in the CD drive, use the "Control E-UAE > Boot CD32 from > CD0:" menu option.

To run a CD32 or CDTV game in a virtual CD drive, use the "Control E-UAE > Boot CD32 from > ICD0:" menu option.  For instructions on mounting an ISO image in a virtual CD drive, please see the @{"6.10. How can I run ISO images of CD32 or CDTV games?" link "6_10"} section.

When you have finished with that game, you can quit E-UAE by pressing Ctrl-Alt-Q.

@{b}Warning!@{ub} When pressing Ctrl-Alt-hotkey in E-UAE, please make sure to press (and hold) the Ctrl key first, followed by the Alt key, followed by the hotkey. Otherwise it will not work.

NOTE: Virtual CDs may be faster than real CDs.

@{b}LIMITATIONS TO BEWARE OF:@{ub}

From my collection of CD32 games, I have found that only 66% of them actually work.  This is due to limitations of E-UAE.

There is no CD32 joypad emulation (!) only plain joystick emulation, so you won't be able to play games which need the CD32's extra buttons.  This is a limitation of E-UAE.

Emulation of CD sound playback needs the analogue sound output of your CD drive connected to an (internal) input on your sound card, otherwise you won't hear any CD music tracks.  Most AmigaOS4 machines probably do NOT have this.

There MAY be an alternative solution for CD sound playback, but I have not tested it.  You need to install a replacement cdplayer.library from OS4Depot:
@{"http://os4depot.net/index.php?function=showfile&file=library/audio/cdplayer_lib.lha" system "OpenURL URL \"http://os4depot.net/index.php?function=showfile&file=library/audio/cdplayer_lib.lha\""}
And you ALSO need to CDDApatch from here:
@{"http://www.amigans.net/modules/xforum/viewtopic.php?topic_id=5143&forum=3&post_id=68914" system "OpenURL URL \"http://www.amigans.net/modules/xforum/viewtopic.php?topic_id=5143&forum=3&post_id=68914\""}
@{"http://dl.dropbox.com/u/26599983/cddapatch.7z" system "OpenURL URL \"http://dl.dropbox.com/u/26599983/cddapatch.7z\""}
Please let me know if this works or not!

While you can change the "frame skip" of the CD32 emulation (using the Control E-UAE menu), you cannot save it, nor can you change other settings (on a per-game) basis.  This is due to RunInUAE not being able to easily identify which game is in the CD drive.


@endnode

@node "4_5" "Using the eGame launcher"
@{fg fill}@{u}4.5. Using the eGame launcher@{uu}@{fg text}
If you want to use a centralised game browser, then eGame works well with RunInUAE.  You can get it from here:
@{"http://os4depot.net/?function=showfile&file=utility/misc/egame.lha" system "OpenURL URL \"http://os4depot.net/?function=showfile&file=utility/misc/egame.lha\""}

To play games using eGame, RunInUAE does NOT need to be running...  UNLESS you want to play non-WHDLoad harddisk-installed games.


@endnode

@node "5_0" "RunInUAE's menus"
@{fg fill}@{u}5. RunInUAE's menus@{uu}@{fg text}
RunInUAE's main window offers some handy menus.

@{"5.1. The Shared settings menu" link "5_1"}
@{"5.2. The Per-game settings menu" link "5_2"}
@{"5.3. The Control E-UAE menu" link "5_3"}
@endnode

@node "5_1" "The Shared settings menu"
@{fg fill}@{u}5.1. The Shared settings menu@{uu}@{fg text}
This menu allows you to change settings that are always used (by E-UAE & RunInUAE).

This menu offers you the option to change:
* Set default joystick to
* Set default screen size to
* Set floppy drive noises to
* ---
* Basic Workbench mode (faster)
* Leave Workbench prefs alone
* ---
* E-UAE time out...
* E-UAE priority...
* E-UAE program...
* E-UAE stay in background

"Set default joystick to" allows you to change the default emulated joystick for @{b}all@{ub} games.  The change will take effect when E-UAE is (re)started.  See the @{"6.2. What are E-UAE's joystick controls?" link "6_2"} section for more info on the "joy1 (main real joystick)" option.

"Set default screen size to" allows you to change the default screen size for @{b}all@{ub} games.  The change will take effect when E-UAE is (re)started.
* "320x256" is the fastest, but not all LCD monitors will support it.
* "320x240" is provided on the chance that some monitors handle it better than 320x256.
* "640x480" is much slower, but it will work with all monitors.
* "window 320x256" opens a window on the Workbench.  This size is the fastest, but may be too small for practical use.
* "window 640x512" opens a window on the Workbench.  This size is much slower, but should be large enough except on the largest monitors.

"Set floppy drive noises to" allows you to change whether E-UAE should have emulated floppy drive noises (via WinUAE sound samples).  "none" means no noises.  "basic" means RunInUAE provides simple emulation.  "full" means E-UAE-amigfx provides realistic noises.


"Basic Workbench mode (faster)" allows you to change the way that programs are started inside E-UAE, in case you have problems starting HD installed games. Games will also start faster, but in theory it could be slightly less compatible.

"Leave Workbench prefs alone" allows power users to prevent RunInUAE from changing Workbench 3.1's screenmode prefs (which it usually does to match the screen size).


"E-UAE time out..." is how long RunInUAE waits for OS3.1 to finish booting in E-UAE, before it gives-up.  It defaults to 20 seconds, but you may need to increase it for slow machines or non-standard OS3 installations.  This settings is @{b}not@{ub} used by Basic Workbench mode.

"E-UAE priority..." is the priority that E-UAE's process is set to run at.  It defaults to 0, although you may want to change this to a value of -1 or 1.  But leave it alone, unless you know what you are doing.

"E-UAE program..." is the E-UAE executable that RunInUAE uses.  Please note that if you switch to an E-UAE executable in a different folder, then you will need to ensure that the following files are copied to that folder:
  .uaerc
  .uaerc_RunInUAE
  .uaerc_RunInUAE.bak
  kick1.3.rom
  kick3.1.rom
  rom.key  (if present)

For CD32 emulation you will also need:
  .uaerc_CD32
  kick3.1-cd32.rom
  kick3.1-ext-cd32.rom

"E-UAE stay in background" allows you to change whether E-UAE's screen is opened in the background.  This is a bit of a kludge, and so doesn't work perfectly. @{i}Please let me know if you find it useful, because I am considering removing this option.@{ui}


@endnode

@node "5_2" "The Per-game settings menu"
@{fg fill}@{u}5.2. The Per-game settings menu@{uu}@{fg text}
This menu allows you to change settings that are specific to the game you last ran OR which you dropped on RunInUAE's window.

This menu offers you the option to:
* Set frame skip to
* Set floppy drive speed to
* Set collision level to
* ---
* Set joystick to
* Set screen size to
* ---
* Manually edit using NotePad
* Prevent game from being run in E-UAE

"Set frame skip to" determines whether any video frames are skipped, @{b}and saves it for the current game@{ub}.  It is worth experimenting with, if you find a game is jerky.  But as it requires restarting E-UAE, you may prefer to first experiment using "Set frame skip to" in the "Control E-UAE" menu (which takes effect immediately, but the setting is not permanent).

"Set floppy drive speed to" determines how fast the floppy drives are, @{b}and saves it for the current game@{ub}.  "x1" is the normal speed, and is the most compatible.  "x8" is the fastest speed, but is the least compatible.  You will have to experiment to find the fastest speed that each ADF game will tolerate.

"Set collision level to" determines what kind of collisions are detected (which can affect emulation speed), @{b}and saves it for the current game@{ub}.  If you have a slow Amiga, then this option might be worth experimenting with.


"Set joystick to" determines what kind of joystick emulation is used, @{b}and saves it for the current game@{ub}.  See the @{"6.2. What are E-UAE's joystick controls?" link "6_2"} section for more info on the "joy1 (main real joystick)" option.

"Set screen size to" determines which screen size is used, @{b}and saves it for the current game@{ub}.  All monitors support "640x480", where-as lower resolutions may not show correctly or at all.
* "320x256" is the fastest, and is best for most games, but does not correctly show High-Res or Interlaced game screens.
* "320x240" is provided on the chance that some monitors handle it better than 320x256.
* "640x480" is much slower, but is ideal for Workbench programs (or games with high-resolution graphics).
* "window 320x256" opens a window on the Workbench.  This size is the fastest, but may be too small for practical use.
* "window 640x512" opens a window on the Workbench.  This size is much slower, but should be large enough except on the largest monitors.


"Manually edit using NotePad" causes the per-game settings to be opened in NotePad, so that power users can manually edit them.

"Prevent game from being run in E-UAE" causes RunInUAE to no-longer redirect the current 68k game into E-UAE (and instead AmigaOS4 will try to run it directly). If you choose this option by mistake, then you can undo it by dropping the game on RunInUAE's window.


@endnode

@node "5_3" "The Control E-UAE menu"
@{fg fill}@{u}5.3. The Control E-UAE menu@{uu}@{fg text}
This menu allows you to command E-UAE to do something (which obviously means E-UAE must already be running).  These changes are never saved, and only affect E-UAE until it quits.

This menu offers you the option to:
* Insert disk in
* Eject disk in
* Set frame skip to
* Save frame skip
* Close E-UAE
* ---
* Relaunch last game
* Boot Workbench
* Boot CD32 from
* ---
* Show log

"Insert disk in" allows you to insert ADF or DMS disk images in the emulated drives.  E-UAE must already be running.

"Eject disk in" allows you to eject disks from the emulated drives.

"Set frame skip to" determines whether any video frames are skipped, and is worth experimenting with if you find a game is jerky (but remember to save this setting!).

"Save frame skip" saves the currently used frame skip setting @{b}for the current game@{ub} (i.e. it changes the per-game settings).

"Close E-UAE" will quit E-UAE.


"Relaunch last game" will re-run the last game again, just as if you had double-clicked it.  It can also be used to restart a game already in progress.

"Boot Workbench" will boot E-UAE into Workbench, without starting any game.

"Boot CD32 from" will boot E-UAE using CD32 emulation.  Use the "CD0:" item to boot from a real CD drive, or use "ICD0:" to boot from a virtual CD image that has already been mounted.

"Show log" shows the log of E-UAE, which may help solving an E-UAE problem.


@endnode

