@endnode

@node "6_1" "How to get RunInUAE working with your monitor"
@{fg fill}@{u}6.1. How to get RunInUAE working with your monitor@{uu}@{fg text}
By default RunInUAE uses a 320x256 screenmode, but initially you may find this doesn't work with your monitor (or it is not full-screen).

The simplest & safest solution is to make RunInUAE use 640x480 instead.  You can do this using the "Shared settings > Set default screen size to > 640x480" menu option for RunInUAE's window.  @{i}But performance will not be quite as good,@{ui} so you may wish to try some of the following options...


If your monitor shows an "out of range" error @{fg shadow}(or similar)@{fg text}, then AmigaOS4 doesn't know the frequency range supported by your monitor.  There are two ways to solve this, listed below, but first please heed the following warning:

@{b}WARNING:  These have a small chance to cause problems booting OS4, so you must ensure you have a backup way to boot AmigaOS4, such as from an OS4 CD or a backup OS4 partition.@{ub} You should also make a backup copy of your Sys:Devs/Monitors folder, so you can then copy this back in the event of a serious problem.

1.  Run Sys:Prefs/ScreenMode, and change to the Monitors tab.  For each 320x256 and 320x240 resolution, click on it, and then on the Remove button.  Then tick "Detect settings automatically" at the top of the window.  Finally click on the "Save Monitor" button.  You MAY reboot here to check that your monitor still works!  You must now reinstall RunInUAE.

2.  Alternatively, if you do NOT want to enable "Detect settings automatically", or you are using an older version of AmigaOS4 that doesn't support this, then you will need to research the horizontal & vertical frequencies @{fg shadow}(Hz)@{fg text} supported by your monitor (I suggest checking the specification of your monitor on the manufacturer's web site).  Once you know them, you need to tell AmigaOS4 about them:

(A) If you ScreenMode prefs program has a Monitors tab, then just enter the correct frequencies under the "Refresh Rate" heading.  Now click "Save Monitor", wait a few seconds, and then reboot.

(B) If you have no Monitors tab, then go to the Sys:Devs/Monitors folder, click on your graphics card's icon, and then use Workbench's "Icon > Information..." menu.  This should open a new window.  Change to the Icon tab, and modify the VSYNCMIN, VSYNCMAX, HSYNCMIN & HSYNCMAX tooltype entries to have the correct frequencies.

In either case (A or B), please beware that HSYNC values should end in 000, because you are entering KHz values as just Hz (thus 31 KHz is 31000 Hz).


@endnode

@node "6_2" "What are E-UAE's joystick controls?"
@{fg fill}@{u}6.2. What are E-UAE's joystick controls?@{uu}@{fg text}
The emulated joystick is currently mapped to the keyboard's Arrow keys for movement, and the Right Alt or Right Ctrl key for fire.  You can change this for one particular game, or change the default for all games:

* "Per-game settings > Set joystick to" menu option changes it for a @{b}single@{ub} game.

* "Shared settings > Set default joystick to" menu option changes the default for @{b}all@{ub} games.  The change will take effect when E-UAE is (re)started.


If you choose "joy1 (main real joystick)", then this will make E-UAE respond to a joystick on Port 1 of AmigaInput's Lowlevel.library emulation.  Here's how you set-up the AmigaInput side, if you haven't already done so:

* Plug in your USB joystick.  You should see a USB message briefly appear.
* Start Sys:Prefs/AmigaInput.

* With the Drivers tab selected, click on USB under Available interfaces.
* You should see your joystick listed under Available drivers, if it is supported.
* Check under Units that you can see it's Status is OK and it's Usage is Enabled.
* With the joystick selected, you can Test/Calibrate it if you want.  (This shouldn't be necessary for digital joysticks, like the Competition Pro.)

* Now go to the LowLevel tab.
* Switch to "Port 1 - Gamepad" (although "Port 1 - Joystick" may also work).
* Select your joystick under Drivers, and then 0 under Units.
* Click the Assign button (which should no-longer be greyed out).

* Now we can finally set-up your joystick.
* Set Red to Button 1.  If you have more buttons, then set Green to Button 2, Blue to Button 3, and Yellow to Button 4.  If you still have spare buttons, then assign them to Reverse, Forward & Start.
* Don't forget to set Horizontal to X-Axis, and Vertical to Y-axis.
* Finally Save your configuration.

* It's now ready for use!  But note that (at least up to AmigaOS4.1 Update 2) the USB joystick won't be recognised upon booting or reset - you need to plug it in @{b}after@{ub} booting.


@endnode

@node "6_3" "How do I connect a joystick to the mouse port?"
@{fg fill}@{u}6.3. How do I connect a joystick to the mouse port?@{uu}@{fg text}
Drop the game onto RunInUAE's window, and then the "Per-game settings > Manually edit using NotePad" menu option.  The settings will open in Notepad.  Then add the following line to the end of the config file:
  joyport0=kbd2


@endnode

@node "6_4" "How do I insert a game's second disk?"
@{fg fill}@{u}6.4. How do I insert a game's second disk?@{uu}@{fg text}
You should not need to do this, if you have named all the game's disks as described in the @{"4.3. Running ADF (& DMS) games" link "4_3"} section.  But if the game does not support multiple floppy drives, then you will need to insert disks manually:

Within E-UAE, press Ctrl-Alt-F1 to open a file requester for the next game disk. It will replace the disk currently in the first disk drive.

Alternatively, use "Insert disk in > drive 1" from RunInUAE's "Control E-UAE" menu.  You will first need to press LeftAmiga-M (or LeftAmiga-N), to get to Workbench where RunInUAE is.


@endnode

@node "6_5" "Can I run AGA games from ADFs?"
@{fg fill}@{u}6.5. Can I run AGA games from ADFs?@{uu}@{fg text}
Yes.  But AGA will only be used if the game's name or folder has the word AGA in it.

Note that AGA games tend to be more demanding, and so you will probably need to set Frame Skip to 1 or 2 (using RunInUAE's "Control E-UAE" menu).  Once you find the ideal setting, remember to save it!

You can also try changing the Collision Level to "none", for a probably tiny improvement in speed.


@endnode

@node "6_6" "How do I install WHDLoad games?"
@{fg fill}@{u}6.6. How do I install WHDLoad games?@{uu}@{fg text}
A WHDLoad game is created from the @{b}original@{ub} game disks (not ADFs!), using a WHDLoad Installer for that particular game.

If you buy a Catweasel PCI card (and a floppy drive) for your AmigaOS4 machine (and have a free PCI slot), then you can use the WHDLoad Installer with AmigaOS4 by following the guide given here:
@{"http://www.retroreview.com/iang/Catweasel/" system "OpenURL URL \"http://www.retroreview.com/iang/Catweasel/\""}

Otherwise the WHDLoad Installer must be run on a @{b}Classic@{ub} Amiga (such as an A1200).  The resulting game files must then be copied from it's harddisk to your Amiga OS4 machine.  I have several suggestions about getting those game files to AmigaOS4:

* Amiga Forever comes with Amiga Explorer & various options for connecting your PC to your Classic Amiga.  You can then copy the files onto a memory stick, etc.

* Directly connect your Classic Amiga's IDE harddrive to your AmigaOS4 machine. If you are using an internal A1200 harddisk, then you will probably need a 2.5" to 3.5" IDE adapter (which are cheap).  If your AmigaOS4 machine is a Sam440, then you will need an IDE to SATA adapter, but these are quite cheap now.

* If your Classic Amiga has been upgraded with a CD writer, then burn your game files onto a CD-R!

* If your Classic Amiga has been upgraded with a USB port, then just use a USB memory stick!


@{b}Alternatively@{ub}, you may find that a WHDLoad version of a game (you already own) is available for download from a web site.


@endnode

@node "6_7" "The arrow keys don't work for my game (e.g. Pinball Fantasies)"
@{fg fill}@{u}6.7. The arrow keys don't work for my game (e.g. Pinball Fantasies)@{uu}@{fg text}
The standard joystick emulation (kbd2) makes the arrow keys acts as the joystick.  Unfortunately this stops the arrow keys being seen by the game, and some such as Pinball Fantasies need the arrow keys.

So for those games you should use the "Per-game settings > Set joystick to" menu to change it to something else.  I suggest kbd1, which uses the number pad.


@endnode

@node "6_8" "Can I have different E-UAE settings for a particular game?"
@{fg fill}@{u}6.8. Can I have different E-UAE settings for a particular game?@{uu}@{fg text}
Yes you can!  By far the easiest way is to drop the game on RunInUAE's window, and then use the "Per-game settings" menu to change settings.  The first time you select an option, it will say it is creating a per-game config file; you must say OK if you want the option to be used.  Advanced users can edit the config file directly, by choosing the "Manually edit using NotePad" menu option.


Alternatively, there are two ways to manually have different settings:  The first is a "per drawer" config file, and the second is a "per game" config file:

* The "per drawer" config file is simply a copy of the ".uaerc_RunInUAE" file (normally found in E-UAE's drawer), which should be placed in the game's drawer. It MUST be called ".uaerc_RunInUAE" .

* The "per game" config file is also a copy of the ".uaerc_RunInUAE" file, but the filename must start with exactly the same name as the game you run.  So if you double-click on the game "Turrican", then it's special config file should be called "Turrican.uaerc_RunInUAE" (and of course it must also be in the same drawer as the game).

You can have special config files for ADFs, but you should @{b}not@{ub} copy the main ".uaerc_RunInUAE" file, unless you need AGA.  Instead create an empty text file with the right name, say using NotePad.


It is important to note that these special config files merely override anything inside E-UAE's main ".uaerc" file, they do no replace it completely.  Also, they will cause E-UAE to always be closed & restarted, if it is already running.


@endnode

@node "6_9" "I want to have a 640x480 screen for Workbench programs"
@{fg fill}@{u}6.9. I want to have a 640x480 screen for Workbench programs@{uu}@{fg text}
Drop the program onto RunInUAE's window, and then choose the "Per-game settings > Set screen size to > 640x480" menu option.  Say OK if it says it will create a per-game config file.


@endnode

@node "6_10" "How can I run ISO images of CD32 or CDTV games?"
@{fg fill}@{u}6.10. How can I run ISO images of CD32 or CDTV games?@{uu}@{fg text}
You need to mount them using DiskImage, and then tell RunInUAE to boot from it using it's "Boot CD32 from > ICD0:" menu option.  To mount an ISO (CD) image in a virtual drive, typically by double-clicking it, you need DiskImage installed.

If DiskImage is not already installed, then please read the @{"6.12. How do I install DiskImage?" link "6_12"} section.


@endnode

@node "6_11" "How can I run HDF games?"
@{fg fill}@{u}6.11. How can I run HDF games?@{uu}@{fg text}
Some games are provided as HDF (Hard Disk File) images.  The easiest way to run them is to mount them using DiskImage, open the disk that appears on Workbench, find the game & then run it @{fg shadow}(using RunInUAE)@{fg text} by double-clicking it.

Here's how you can set-up DiskImage to mount a HDF image when you double-click it:

You need DiskImage installed.  If it isn't, then please read the @{"6.12. How do I install DiskImage?" link "6_12"} section, and come back here when you are done.

Start Sys:Prefs/DefIcons, then scroll down to & select "diskarchive" @{fg shadow}(or just "archive" if you can't find it)@{fg text} in the Filetypes list.  Click on the Add button at the bottom of the list, and in the Name field delete "«new»", type "hdf" (without quotes), and then press the Enter key.

Under the Actions box click on the Add...  button, and choose PATTERN.  In the Pattern field that appears underneath, you should type "#?.hdf" (without quotes), and then press the Enter key.

Finally click on the Save button.


@endnode

@node "6_12" "How do I install DiskImage?"
@{fg fill}@{u}6.12. How do I install DiskImage?@{uu}@{fg text}
@{b}If you are already using Update 4 (or later)@{ub} of AmigaOS4.1, then please download DiskImage from OS4Depot:
@{"http://os4depot.net/index.php?function=showfile&file=driver/storage/diskimage_device.lha" system "OpenURL URL \"http://os4depot.net/index.php?function=showfile&file=driver/storage/diskimage_device.lha\""}
Install this version, as it is compatible with Update 4.  @{fg shadow}(If you install the version of DiskImage that comes with Update 1 (as a Contribution), then it will overwrite Update 4's DefIcons preferences (which may cause problems).)@{fg text}

If you want to use DiskImageGUI, then you also need to install AISS:
@{"http://os4depot.net/index.php?function=showfile&file=graphics/aiss/aiss.lha" system "OpenURL URL \"http://os4depot.net/index.php?function=showfile&file=graphics/aiss/aiss.lha\""}

@{b}If you are using Update 3 or earlier@{ub} of AmigaOS4.1, then please install DiskImage from Update 1.  You can do this using the Extras Installer on AmiDock, or if you removed that then you can find the Extras Installer in the hidden "Sys:Utilities/InstallExtras" folder @{fg shadow}(once in the Utilities folder, use Workbench's "Window > Show > All files" menu option to unhide it)@{fg text}.

When choosing to install "DiskImage Device", please ALSO ensure that you install "AISS" (which is needed by DiskImageGUI).

@{b}If you are using AmigaOS4.0@{ub}, then you will have to install DiskImage from OS4Depot, as described earlier.  In this case you will be missing the DefIcons preferences need for double-clicking ADF, DMS, ISO & HDF files.  For ADF & DMS files, you will have to drop them on RunInUAE's icon in AmiDock or it's AppIcon. While for ISO & HDF files, you will have to use DiskImageGUI (to mount them in ICD0: & IDF0: respectively.)

@{b}In any case@{ub}, please reboot after installation!


@endnode

@node "6_13" "My HD installed games cannot save.  Help!"
@{fg fill}@{u}6.13. My HD installed games cannot save.  Help!@{uu}@{fg text}
This is because (for safety) RunInUAE makes your Amiga harddisk appear read-only to E-UAE.

It is best if you tell your games to save to the "SaveGames" disk @{fg shadow}(which is automatically inserted into E-UAE's virtual floppy drive DF0)@{fg text}.  However, if you need to allow E-UAE to make changes to your harddrive, then:

1.  Double-click on the ".uaerc_RunInUAE" file in E-UAE's folder.  This should open it in NotePad.

2.  At the bottom you should see several lines that begin with "filesystem2=ro" , each followed by a volume name.

3.  Look for the volume that contains your games, and change it's line from "=ro" to "=rw".  Thus the line should now begin "filesystem2=rw" .

4.  Finally click on Save.  Your changes will be used the next time E-UAE starts.


@endnode

@node "6_14" "DAX's tricks & tips for an authentic look using CRT"
@{fg fill}@{u}6.14. DAX's tricks & tips for an authentic look using CRT@{uu}@{fg text}
If you are a retro-nut who wants E-UAE to look exactly like your A500 did on an old TV, then you can thank DAX for reporting how to achieve this using a CRT (an LCD won't do).  For more information please read his thread here:
@{"http://amigaworld.net/modules/newbb/viewtopic.php?topic_id=33347&forum=8" system "OpenURL URL \"http://amigaworld.net/modules/newbb/viewtopic.php?topic_id=33347&forum=8\""}

Not only do you get an authentic "Amiga on a TV" look, but it reduces subtle stuttering & tearing with scrolling which some people may notice.


@endnode

@node "6_15" "Authentic look using LCD"
@{fg fill}@{u}6.15. Authentic look using LCD@{uu}@{fg text}
Those with an LCD monitor, who don't wish to use a CRT, can get a more authentic look using the method given below.  But please note that I don't recommend it for Sam440 & MicroA1 users who aren't already using a 640x480 screenmode.

1.  Choose 640x480 as your default screen resolution (using Shared settings > Set default screen size to > 640x480).  This will reduce the performance of E-UAE, particularly on Sam440s & MicroA1s, unless you were already using 640x480.

2.  Then go to your E-UAE folder, open the ".uaerc" file by double-clicking it (should get loaded by NotePad), scroll down to the bottom, find the following lines:

  gfx_linemode=double
  gfx_correct_aspect=yes

and change them to:

  gfx_linemode=scanlines
  gfx_correct_aspect=no

Beware that this may also cause problems with a few games, as I have not thoroughly tested this solution.

@endnode

@node "6_16" "How the different E-UAE config files are used by RunInUAE"
@{fg fill}@{u}6.16. How the different E-UAE config files are used by RunInUAE@{uu}@{fg text}
You should not normally need to know this, but someone wanted to know about the different E-UAE config files that RunInUAE uses.

RunInUAE is limited by what E-UAE supports.  E-UAE only allows two config files to be loaded at once, with the second config file overriding anything that exists (conflicts) in the first config file.

So RunInUAE has a shared settings file called ".uaerc" (actually an A500 config), and then gives a second config file to E-UAE depending on the circumstance:

* In case of A500 games (basically ADFs), no second config file is needed... unless there is a per-game config file.  @{fg shadow}(Newly created per-game config files are empty.)@{fg text}

* In the case of ADFs that need AGA, the second config file is ".uaerc_RunInUAE".  @{fg shadow}(If a per-game config file is created, then this is a copy of the ".uaerc_RunInUAE" file, rather than being empty.)@{fg text}

* In the case of HD installed games (WHDLoad or otherwise) then the second config file is ".uaerc_RunInUAE".  @{fg shadow}(If a per-game config file is created, then this is a copy of the ".uaerc_RunInUAE" file, rather than being empty.)@{fg text}

* In the case of CDTV & CD32 games, the second config file is ".uaerc_CD32".


@{fg shadow}(Note that per-game config files may sound complicated, but RunInUAE will happily create the correct 'empty' config file for you (just drop the game on the RunInUAE Window, and then choose the "Per-game settings > Set screen size to > 640x480" menu option).  You then merely need to add any required settings to the end of the config file.)@{fg text}


@endnode

@node "6_17" "I've changed my E-UAE settings, and now it doesn't work properly."
@{fg fill}@{u}6.17. I've changed my E-UAE settings, and now it doesn't work properly.@{uu}@{fg text}
Best to undo the changes you made, but you might also be able to guess the problem by looking at E-UAE's log:  Go to RunInUAE's window, open the "Control E-UAE" menu, and choose the "Show log" menu option.

In the worst case, you may need to reinstall RunInUAE.  In that case make sure to say yes to replacing the ".uaerc" config files!  If that doesn't work, then you can try using the UNinstaller before re-installing RunInUAE from scratch.

@endnode

@node "6_18" "HELP! RunInUAE doesn't work for me :-("
@{fg fill}@{u}6.18. HELP! RunInUAE doesn't work for me :-(@{uu}@{fg text}
Please send a FULL description of your problem to my email address, which you can find in the @{"8. Last words & contact details" link "8_0"} chapter.  Things to include that will REALLY help me:

1. The EXACT error message, and all the steps needed to see it.

2. The version of RunInUAE you are using.

3. The version of AmigaOS4 (including any updates) that you are using.

4. What machine you are using (e.g. Sam460 with a RadeonHD 4650 graphics card).

5. Please run the "Debug_Backup" program that comes with the RunInUAE installer.  It will create a complete backup of your RunInUAE installation, which you can then attach to your email.  This will be REALLY helpful in finding your problem.

6. If you are getting a Grim Reaper, then please click on the "More..." button, and then the "Write Crash Log" button.  This will create a Crashlog file in RAM:.  Please attach this crash log to your email.


@endnode

@node "7_0" "The future"
@{fg fill}@{u}7. The future@{uu}@{fg text}
RunInUAE now does most of what I wanted it to do, although I do have a few more ideas that @{i}may or may not get implemented@{ui}, such as:

* Replace most of the menus with a proper GUI (which should be more intuitive to use).

* An internal (non-user-visible!) rewrite to use my standard modules for patching, threading & sound.


If you are interested in any of these ideas, or have any suggestions of your own, then feel free to email me!  Your input may help me decided what to do next.


@endnode

@node "8_0" "Last words & contact details"
@{fg fill}@{u}8. Last words & contact details@{uu}@{fg text}
If you have any problems with RunInUAE, then please let me know!  I have done my best to make it "just work", but there are a lot of things that could go wrong. You can contact me by email, using the address given on this web page:

@{"http://cshandley.co.uk/email" system "OpenURL URL \"http://cshandley.co.uk/email\""}

If for some reason you cannot email me, then I can be found on AmigaWorld.net & www.Amigans.net as "ChrisH".  I suggest you PM me on AmigaWorld.net, as I may not notice forum posts (nor PMs on Amigans.net!).


@{"8.1. Thanks to" link "8_1"}
@endnode

@node "8_1" "Thanks to"
@{fg fill}@{u}8.1. Thanks to@{uu}@{fg text}
RunInUAE would be much worse (or might not even exist at all!) without the help of many people.  In chronological order, thanks to:

* Philippe Rimauro, whose UAELoad implementation inspired me to write RunInUAE. RunInUAE would not exist without it!

* davebraco, for providing RunInUAE's icon & help beta testing it.

* David 'DAX' Rinaldi, for help beta testing it, as well as ideas & suggestions.

* Some members of AmigaWorld.net & Amigans.net for reporting what their Amiga Forever CDs contain.

* Mike Battilana from Cloanto, for help with unreported Amiga Forever CDs.

* Many people on Amigans.net & AmigaWorld.net for reporting problems, bugs & suggestions!

* Michael Trebilcock for E-UAE-amigfx, and various hints about E-UAE.

* Colin Wenzel for his help improving patching for all versions of AmigaOS4.

* Philippe Ferrucci, for beta testing & ideas.

* Too many AmigaOS4 beta testers to mention (sorry!) for testing RunInUAE.

* Hans de Ruiter, for help understanding & working-around a RadeonHD issue.

* Hyperion, for their AmigaOS Wiki, especially relating to Intuition menus.  And for AmigaOS4 of course!

* Virginio Vazquez (R), for beta testing.

* Jesús Fernández, Oleg K, Mehdi Boulahia & Scott Cabit, for finding bugs in beta versions of RunInUAE.

Sorry if I forgot anyone.


@endnode

